    <subsection>
        <title>Exponent Basics</title>
        <p>Let's remind ourselves of some important vocabulary for expressions with exponents: <me>\text{base}^{\text{exponent}} = \text{power}</me> So when we calculate <m>8^{2} = 64</m>, the <term>base</term> is <m>8</m>, the <term>exponent</term> is <m>2</m>, and the expression <m>8^{2}</m> is called the 2nd <term>power</term> of 8. Many people refer to exponents as ``powers'' as well<mspace />like every other language, mathematical vocabulary has never been completely standardized.</p>

        <p>Remember that if an exponent is a positive integer, the power can be rewritten as a product, that is, as repeated multiplication of the base. For example, the 4th power of <m>-3</m> can be written as <m>4</m> factors of <m>-3</m> like so:<me>(-3)^{4} = (-3)(-3)(-3)(-3).</me> If we're willing to write out powers as  products carefully, every exponent <q>rule</q> makes senses. So let's warm up by practicing writing products.</p>

